Just finished reading Spare in the Trunk
Something I really liked is how much attention you've paid to them trying to figure out her place in his world, it makes them both (but her in particular) feel really like people instead of characters. Her mix of shame for her low place in the world and almost vengeful pride in the few things she does have (even if they're shit) is really realistic, and the way they're going about trying to improve themselves for each other (and how that's affecting their own views and relationships with other people) is interesting and I hope to see that explored more. You've also got a lot of attention to detail with elements of their characterization; they feel like they always have a reason for what they say and do.
Something that struck me as odd, though, is how Lys seems to occasionally approach things from a human perspective before she does a kobold's, such as in chapter 3 when she astutely comments how Jack is 'brave' for being willing to be seen in public in proximity to a kobold. It's an odd thing for someone in her position to be both knowledgeable and compassionate on; I would have thought that an eternal scavenger would have different criteria than that for being brave. If that's a deliberate part of her characterization, like if she has some reason to have those human elements to her thoughts that you haven't covered yet, then fair enough. It just struck me as odd that neither he nor she seemed to notice it then or anywhere else
That's the only thing that's really felt off in the story to me, though, and it's just a minor detail. I hope more is coming soon and I hope there's not gonna be a massive falling out with that human chick, I feel like she deserves better with how nice she's being. I also hope that Rodil guy isn't going to end up causing more problems for them, his presence feels like it has potential to ruin everything she's got. Good drama
Really liked it all in all and I want to see where it goes next
